# Tier 7 (gamut matrix / primaries conversion) baseline
# Date: 2026-04-23  |  Commit: fb92135  |  Hardware: AMD Ryzen 9 7950X
# Command: cargo bench --bench bench_t7_gamut
#
# Throughput at 4096px:
#
#   Linear F32 gamut (P3→BT.709)                      21.84 GiB/s
#   Linear F32 gamut (BT.2020→BT.709)                 21.63 GiB/s
#   sRGB U8 → Linear F32 + gamut (P3→BT.709)          11.19 GiB/s
#   sRGB U16 fused gamut (P3→BT.709)                   5.84 GiB/s
#   sRGB U8 fused gamut (P3→BT.709)                    3.79 GiB/s
#   Linear F32 → sRGB U8 + gamut (P3→BT.709)           3.11 GiB/s
#
# Findings:
#
# 1. **Standalone Linear F32 gamut (GamutMatrixRgbF32) at ~22 GiB/s** —
#    a 3×3 f32 matrix multiply per pixel, autovecs well. Gamut is the
#    cheapest step once we're in linear F32.
#
# 2. **sRGB U8 fused gamut at 3.79 GiB/s** — FusedSrgbU8GamutRgb does
#    LUT linearize → matrix → LUT encode in one pass. Comparable to
#    Linear F32 → sRGB U8 alone at 4.56 GiB/s in T3; the added gamut
#    matrix is essentially free because it's amortized into the
#    LUT-to-matrix-to-LUT pipeline (where the LUT encode dominates).
#
# 3. **sRGB U16 fused gamut at 5.84 GiB/s** — slightly faster than the
#    U8 version at the same size. Surprising; probably LLVM vectorizing
#    the matrix better with wider register-efficient u16 path.
#
# 4. **Linear F32 → sRGB U8 + gamut at 3.11 GiB/s** — the slowest of the
#    gamut paths. Inherits the Linear→sRGB OETF cost (same asymmetry noted
#    in T3). The matrix is nearly free; the bottleneck is the per-lane
#    sRGB encoding.
#
# 5. **sRGB U8 → Linear F32 + gamut at 11.19 GiB/s** — roughly 2× faster
#    than the reverse, same reason: forward sRGB LUT is 1-cycle, reverse
#    is rational poly + divide.
#
# Action items:
#   - Gamut itself is fine; no dedicated work needed.
#   - The L→sRGB slowness is a T3 issue (the OETF), not a T7 issue. Any
#    fix there (e.g., larger LUT approach in linear-srgb) would also
#    speed up the fused gamut kernels.
